00:00:22.232 --> 00:00:23.690
MICHAEL SHORT: So
as a quick review

00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:26.180
of all the different
biological effects,

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:30.080
we've pretty much
taken it up to here.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.870
We've explained the
physical and chemical stages

00:00:32.870 --> 00:00:34.730
of what happens when
radiation interacts

00:00:34.730 --> 00:00:37.970
with mostly bags of water with
some solutes in them, better

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:41.300
known as organisms at
dynamic equilibrium.

00:00:41.300 --> 00:00:45.590
Everything from the sort of
femptosecond level, ionization

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:47.450
of water almost
certainly, because that's

00:00:47.450 --> 00:00:50.240
most of what
biological things are,

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:55.610
to the formation of many, many,
many, many, many different

00:00:55.610 --> 00:01:00.260
radiolysis byproducts eventually
that end up as just a few

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:02.840
that we care about, the
longer-lived radiolytic

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:06.200
byproducts that will
then diffuse away

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:08.600
from the original
damage cascades

00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:13.490
and go on to eat something
else, likely DNA or something

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:18.680
that you don't want to get
oxidized or chemically changed.

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:21.797
We talked a little bit
about radiolysis in reactors

00:01:21.797 --> 00:01:23.630
and how you can actually
measure it directly

00:01:23.630 --> 00:01:27.470
which was only done really a few
years ago which is pretty cool.

00:01:27.470 --> 00:01:29.270
Just to remind you
of this experiment,

00:01:29.270 --> 00:01:31.250
there's a tiny
high-pressure cell

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:33.270
of high-pressure,
high-temperature water.

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:37.130
There is a foil sample with a
very thin region and protons

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:40.100
firing through it, so that
they both irradiate the sample

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:43.690
and induce radiolysis in
the water at the same time.

00:01:43.690 --> 00:01:46.640
And this way, you can test
the effect of radiolysis

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:49.430
in the water here versus just
plain, old, high-pressure,

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:51.410
high-temperature corrosion here.

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:53.510
And the results are
pretty striking,

00:01:53.510 --> 00:01:56.600
where you can clearly see
the boundary where the proton

00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:00.380
beam was as well as
the increased thickness

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:03.630
of the oxide and corrosion
layer formed when radiolysis

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:06.650
is turned on, so to speak.

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:11.820
We went through DNA damage, and
we ended with pseudoscience.

