00:02:56.950 --> 00:03:00.080
It's pretty easy to cherry
pick small amounts of data.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:03.430
I did want to say that just
because radio frequency

00:03:03.430 --> 00:03:07.720
photons aren't ionizing, doesn't
mean they can't hurt you.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:12.250
If you've ever-- no, no one's
ever been inside a microwave.

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:14.170
I wonder if anyone's
ever felt the effects

00:03:14.170 --> 00:03:16.990
of an external microwave
being by something like this,

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:18.400
the active denial system.

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:22.210
One of my favorite weapons ever,
because it doesn't actually

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:24.190
permanently hurt anyone.

00:03:24.190 --> 00:03:26.890
It just heats up the
outer layer of your skin.

00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:30.850
It fires these non-ionizing
photons at RF frequency

00:03:30.850 --> 00:03:34.180
and effectively makes you
feel like you're on fire.

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:36.610
So if there's a whole mess
of troops charging at you--

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:40.600
let's say at the DMZ from
North and South Korea--

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:42.910
all you've got to do
is turn on this thing,

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:44.470
and they all think
they're on fire,

00:03:44.470 --> 00:03:47.380
because their body is sending
them signals that I'm on fire.

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:49.390
And then you turn it
off, and they're OK.

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:52.480
So no loss of life,
no permanent damage,

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:54.730
a lot of maybe
psychological, but whatever,

00:03:54.730 --> 00:03:56.820
you can't see that.

00:03:56.820 --> 00:03:57.820
AUDIENCE: Active denial.

00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:00.580
MICHAEL SHORT: Active denial
system, great name for it,

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:01.210
isn't it?

00:04:01.210 --> 00:04:03.335
Yeah, I think non-lethal
weapons are really the way

00:04:03.335 --> 00:04:07.270
of the future is just make
it unpleasant to engage

00:04:07.270 --> 00:04:09.790
in warfare, and
people probably won't.

00:04:09.790 --> 00:04:13.720
But then no one has to
get hurt, which is nice.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:16.600
But then onto the sources of
data, because like Sarah said,

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:19.660
sample size is everything,
especially when you're

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:22.210
trying to figure out, are
small amounts of radiation

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:23.110
bad for you?

00:04:23.110 --> 00:04:25.210
This simple question
hasn't really

00:04:25.210 --> 00:04:28.960
been answered suitably yet,
and that's because, thank god,

00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:31.600
we don't have enough
people exposed

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:33.730
to small but measurable
amounts of radiation

00:04:33.730 --> 00:04:37.300
to draw meaningful
conclusions from this data.

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:40.810
I think that's a good thing,
is if we were certain about

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:42.730
whether small
amounts of radiation,

00:04:42.730 --> 00:04:44.795
like one millisieverts,
could cause cancer,

00:04:44.795 --> 00:04:47.170
then there would have been
millions or billions of people

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:49.900
exposed, and so it's kind of a
good thing that they weren't.

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:52.510
But the sources of this
data, the first source

00:04:52.510 --> 00:04:55.522
was radium dial workers,
like you may have heard of,

00:04:55.522 --> 00:04:57.730
the folks that would lick
the paint brushes with glow

00:04:57.730 --> 00:04:59.560
in the dark radium watches.

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:04.090
They ended up setting the first
occupational limit for dose,

00:05:04.090 --> 00:05:05.950
because they were
the first large group

00:05:05.950 --> 00:05:09.220
to be exposed to radiation
in a controlled setting.

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:12.400
Things like uranium miners,
radon breathers, better known

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:15.880
as us, but especially
folks that smoke anything.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:19.840
Medical diagnostics, so anyone
that gets a medical procedure,

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:22.060
you can follow up with them
to find out what's, let's

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:24.820
say, the extra incidence
of cancer and figure

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:27.880
out, if you have a
high-dose medical procedure,

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:30.520
does it induce secondary
cancer down the line?

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:33.810
But like we said last time,
down the line is the key here.

00:05:33.810 --> 00:05:35.780
I'd take a whole
bunch of radiation

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:38.830
now, if it was going to
save my life now, and maybe

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:40.150
make it messed up in 20 years.

00:05:40.150 --> 00:05:42.100
Because then you get
20 more years of life

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:43.800
or however long you get.

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:45.670
And then from
accidents, survivors

00:05:45.670 --> 00:05:48.610
of the atomic bombs, not just
the folks at the epicenter,

00:05:48.610 --> 00:05:51.610
but in the whole fallout
regions and nearby, as well as

00:05:51.610 --> 00:05:54.970
nearby nuclear accidents
and the criticality events

00:05:54.970 --> 00:05:58.000
like the demon core that you
guys analyzed on the exam.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.340
Luckily, there aren't
a lot of those, either.

00:06:00.340 --> 00:06:03.260
But they were pretty severe,
the ones that got exposed.

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:05.260
And speaking of accidents,
has anyone ever heard

00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:08.150
of the Kyshtym disaster?

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:10.430
This is the third-worst
nuclear accident

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:13.760
that we know of in history,
after Chernobyl and Fukushima,

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:15.560
and worse than
Three Mile Island,

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:18.620
because Three Mile Island
was an almost accident.

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:21.050
There was some partial
melting of the core.

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:23.630
There was almost no
release of radioactivity.

00:06:23.630 --> 00:06:26.420
And the definition of a nuclear
accident in the public sense

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:28.490
is release of radioactivity.

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:31.040
There's actually two
quantities that folks

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:33.680
in PRA, or Probabilistic
Risk Analysis,

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:34.790
are most interested in.

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:38.630
Has anyone heard of these
terms, CDF and LERF?

00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:43.400
Core Damage Frequency and
Large Early Release Frequency.

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:46.640
All the fancy probability
fault trees and everything

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:48.500
goes into calculating
the probability

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:50.300
that the core gets damaged.

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:52.280
So that could be an
accident in one right.

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:54.380
Or the probability of a
radioactivity release.

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:56.163
And that is an accident.

00:06:56.163 --> 00:06:57.580
So if no one's
ever heard of this,

00:06:57.580 --> 00:06:59.920
there's a city in Russia--

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:01.990
I don't know why it says
Russland, maybe came

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:04.390
from a different language--

00:07:04.390 --> 00:07:06.310
called Kyshtym, where
they had the Mayak

00:07:06.310 --> 00:07:08.970
nuclear and reprocessing plant.

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:12.010
And there was a tank
full of radioactive waste

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:13.450
that was exploded.

00:07:13.450 --> 00:07:17.140
It was a chemical explosion,
but full of strontium,

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:19.210
all sorts of other
radionuclides that

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:22.270
blew up with about
100 tons worth of TNT,

00:07:22.270 --> 00:07:25.360
and ended up contaminating
a rather large area

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:27.700
with this plume called the--

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:30.600
I think it's called the East
Chelyabinsk Radioactive Trace--

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:31.370
or the--

00:07:31.370 --> 00:07:31.870
what is it?

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:35.380
The south-- South-something
Urals Radioactive Trace.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.960
And that area is still
contaminated today,

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:41.260
because the disaster was
covered up, or rather wasn't--

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:42.430
nothing was said.

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:44.290
These towns here, they didn't--

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:47.913
weren't actually towns back
in 1957 when this happened.

00:07:47.913 --> 00:07:49.330
They were just
given designations,

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:52.660
like Chelyabinsk-40
or Chelyabinsk-65,

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:56.110
because the largest nearby
city was Chelyabinsk,

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:58.360
and the villages nearby
were just numbered.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:01.540
So that was just the post code
for the secret nuclear city.

00:08:01.540 --> 00:08:05.412
The US had a few, Russia
had something like 120.

00:08:05.412 --> 00:08:06.870
And they still have
a lot of cities

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:11.070
where entry is restricted, or
it's still awfully difficult

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:11.580
to go there.

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:14.250
Like when you have to declare
where in Russia are you going

00:08:14.250 --> 00:08:16.320
to get a visa, if you
say one of these cities,

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:18.693
there's going to
be some questions.

00:08:18.693 --> 00:08:19.860
And this is where I'm going.

00:08:19.860 --> 00:08:22.175
AUDIENCE: To one
of those cities.

00:08:22.175 --> 00:08:23.550
MICHAEL SHORT:
Best possible logo

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:28.080
for a conference being held
in Siberia in February.

00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:29.148
Right on the end--

00:08:29.148 --> 00:08:30.690
right on the edge
in this town called

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:33.780
Kyshtym, the nearest
town to the Mayak plant.

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:35.220
So I'll be taking my camera.

00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:37.090
I don't know if I'll
be allowed to use it,

00:08:37.090 --> 00:08:38.971
but we're going to
find out anyway.

00:08:38.971 --> 00:08:40.304
It's being held in a sanatorium.

00:08:40.304 --> 00:08:43.130
And does anyone know
what a sanatorium is?

00:08:43.130 --> 00:08:45.260
Like, I'm honestly
asking a question.

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:46.940
I don't know what
a sanatorium is

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:49.370
or why the nuclear conference
is being held there.

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:52.060
But it should be pretty cool.

00:08:52.060 --> 00:08:55.090
So yeah, Siberia in February,
right near the South Urals

00:08:55.090 --> 00:08:57.520
Radioactive Trace,
should be interesting.

00:08:57.520 --> 00:08:59.960
Those of the first group
of folks that were exposed

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:03.010
were the people painting
radium watch dials.

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:05.140
And the reason radium
was so damaging is

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:08.410
because radium is in the same
column of the periodic table

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:09.580
as calcium.

00:09:09.580 --> 00:09:11.290
It's a bone-seeking element.

00:09:11.290 --> 00:09:12.790
So which of the
tissues do you think

00:09:12.790 --> 00:09:17.350
would be most damaged
by ingestion of radium?

00:09:17.350 --> 00:09:18.240
AUDIENCE: The bones.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:20.290
MICHAEL SHORT: Bones-- what
part of the bone, specifically?

00:09:20.290 --> 00:09:21.257
AUDIENCE: The marrow.

00:09:21.257 --> 00:09:22.340
MICHAEL SHORT: The marrow.

00:09:22.340 --> 00:09:24.440
The rapidly dividing
part of the bones.

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:27.110
If you remember from the--

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:29.420
I don't have it on
this presentation,

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:33.260
but the relative tissue
factors for different tissues,

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:35.900
the hard part of
the bone is a 0.01.

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:37.880
It's basically like
a nobody cares.

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:39.680
Bone marrow, however,
is a different story,

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:42.740
because it's always rapidly
dividing, producing red blood

00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:45.490
cells, platelets, lymphocytes.

00:09:45.490 --> 00:09:49.460
It's making your blood, the
solid portion of your blood.

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:52.160
And so it's a pretty
important tissue.

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:54.440
So you get radium--

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:56.450
anyone also know, what
does radium tend to emit?

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:02.262
Which kind of particles?

00:10:02.262 --> 00:10:03.190
AUDIENCE: Alphas.

00:10:03.190 --> 00:10:04.940
MICHAEL SHORT: If you have to
take a guess-- yeah, alphas.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:06.500
It's a pretty heavy element.

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:07.880
It emits alphas.

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:11.450
And alphas have that radiation
quality factor of 20,

00:10:11.450 --> 00:10:13.620
meaning alphas have
very short range,

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:15.710
but they're the most
damaging type of radiation

00:10:15.710 --> 00:10:16.880
when ingested.

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:18.210
So this was really bad news.

00:10:18.210 --> 00:10:20.870
There was a lot of incidents
of illness and cancer

00:10:20.870 --> 00:10:23.330
from folks painting
radium watch dials.

00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:25.980
And then the first data
from bones after death,

00:10:25.980 --> 00:10:28.310
because there were a lot
of those, established,

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:31.040
how much radium were you
allowed to get exposed to?

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:34.580
And this came out to about
0.6 milligray per week.

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:36.080
Anyone have any
idea what that would

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.060
be in millisieverts per week?

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:41.810
With a quality factor
of 20 and a bone marrow

00:10:41.810 --> 00:10:46.888
factor of about 0.12?

00:10:46.888 --> 00:10:48.750
AUDIENCE: 1.73?

00:10:48.750 --> 00:10:49.680
MICHAEL SHORT: Yeah.

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:54.740
On the order of like singles
of millisieverts per week.

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:55.340
Not bad.

00:10:55.340 --> 00:10:56.965
Anyone know how much
dose you typically

00:10:56.965 --> 00:10:59.880
get in a year in background?

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:00.380
Yeah?

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:01.280
AUDIENCE: A few.

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:03.030
MICHAEL SHORT: A few
millisieverts a year.

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:03.810
Yeah.

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:06.390
So this was the first
occupational safety

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:08.070
limit for radiation risk.

00:11:08.070 --> 00:11:11.130
It is-- actually, it comes out
to larger than 50 millisieverts

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:14.250
per year, which is what the
normal occupational workers are

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:15.090
allowed.

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:16.900
How about you radiation workers?

00:11:16.900 --> 00:11:17.910
What's your limit?

00:11:17.910 --> 00:11:18.900
AUDIENCE: 5 rem.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:20.950
MICHAEL SHORT: 5 rem,
which comes out to?

00:11:20.950 --> 00:11:22.545
AUDIENCE: Like 50
millisieverts--

00:11:22.545 --> 00:11:23.320
MICHAEL SHORT: 50
millisieverts per year.

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:24.060
OK, there you go.

00:11:26.630 --> 00:11:28.633
Large population
sizes that do exist

00:11:28.633 --> 00:11:30.050
